The other day I asked you why the new paper pad from @sketchbar__club was named “The Mirror”, and most of you guessed it! This is double-sided paper that doesn’t allow any type of bleed through, even on the opposite side of the page! You can draw on both sides of the sheet and your drawings won’t show through to the other side, no matter how much you saturate the page.
Compared to other paper pads I’ve used, this is by far my favorite one and will be my go-to from now on. I don’t know about you, but I’m tired of only using half the paper on a $20+ paper pad 💀. I’ll be experimenting on this paper from now on and I’ll post a few more reviews in photo form when I get the chance. Highly recommend this paper, and alsoooo you can get 15% off this paper on the @sketchbar__club website by using my code: drawntworks

👾 BITTERSWEET POST 👾

A handful of work I did for a cancelled 2D platformer game set in Cyberpunk Kyoto. Sadly, it seems this project will never see the light of day, due to lack of funding, but I’m so happy I was able to dedicate time to it otherwise. 

Throughout the process, I learned a lot about visual development, asset creation, technical skills inside the Unity engine, and even a bit of coding in C#. 

I really enjoyed dressing up the test levels with all the art I was making, and there is, without a doubt, no feeling like walking around in a world you conceptualized! By far my favorite part, and even if this was my last time working on a game, I will always cherish the experience. 

I’m hoping to get the opportunity to try my hand at this again sometime in the future 😊. 

Also, I’ll be attending the @pigsquadpdx Art/Code/Game night tomorrow at @wacom.experience.pdx ! Is anyone else going? 😁

Some character design and exploration I did on a project for a recent client. I was lucky enough to be given complete freedom with the personalities of each character, and took this time to practice my character development skills. 

I feel like I pushed myself in the right direction with these sketches. It’s been awhile since I’ve explored the actual behaviors and expressions of my characters - something that makes them feel more “real”. I had a lot of fun with it!

Also, yes I am open to working on commissions or a project you might have in mind. If you’re interested in working together, please send me a DM!

✨👾 My new setup 👾✨

Growing up, there was rarely a time I wasn’t clutching a controller and traversing through the in-game worlds of my favorite titles. My time spent inside these worlds were a significant escape from the harsh realities I faced growing up. Gaming quickly became a huge part of my life, and as I grew older it become more apparent that pursuing a career in video games is where my passion lies. At first, it felt like an impossible goal; a marketing student with no considerable skills that could land me a job in this field. It wasn’t until a friend of mine gifted me an online course for 2D development in Unity that I finally took the dive. Thanks @senpaislik !

This next year will mark my third year in game development—primarily working as a 2D Art Generalist (occasionally wearing the technical artist hat) for a handful of clients and indie studios; and I couldn’t be happier! 

My experience as an artist in the Indie game industry so far is filled with ups and downs. Mostly downs, probably due to my overly ambitious tendencies—but these experiences taught me a lot and I believe they’ve paved the way for future successful projects. Some important things I’ve learned, not just as a game dev, but a freelancer in general, is that you just have to keep pushing. You have to be persistent. You have to have thick skin. That fear of rejection and the overbearing dread that accompanies failure are your worst enemies, and you are the only person who can break through those walls. 

Little things, like this new setup, help keep the flame burning, providing me with the energy to push through those tough periods. Don’t forget to treat yourself, it is one of the integral parts of any journey 💆🏻‍♂️

You can stay updated on the game that my friends and I are developing @gobblefishgames 🐟

👾 Pom Update 👾

These past few weeks, we’ve been working more on developing lighting, atmosphere, and platforming challenges for our demo build. In this example, we wanted to focus on the verticality that is present in some of levels; showcasing how abilities might be used in conjunction to traverse our world! 

Timing and positioning will become more complex as the game goes on, but the earlier stages will help train your reaction speeds as you move forward 🕹️✨ 

For more updates on our project, make sure to turn on post notification for @drawntworks and our studio page @gobblefishgames 🐟

👾 Pom Update 👾

In case you missed it in the last few posts, this is Herbert, the player character in our upcoming challenge platformer game. He’s gone through a few different phases in the past year, but we’ve landed on a solid design that we’re really proud of! 

Herbert is the last orange puffball in the entire Pom star system; on a mission to purge the infectious Blue Goop that plagues his world. Will he be able to revert the damage that his once best friend, Ernest, has brought upon Pom? 

For more updates on project, feel free to follow @gobblefishgames 🐟
